00:10:39.204 --> 00:10:42.307
- Yeah, that worked.
- I was so scared. [laughing]

00:10:42.340 --> 00:10:44.743 align:start position:0%
I was so close to, like,
going to, like,

00:10:44.776 --> 00:10:46.278 align:start position:0%
just say, "You know what?
I changed my mind."

00:10:46.311 --> 00:10:48.147 size:81% position:41%
I was so close to leaving.

00:10:48.180 --> 00:10:50.949 align:end position:100%
- You did say that you felt
a prickle.

00:10:50.982 --> 00:10:53.152
- Uh-huh.
- How do you feel about that?

00:10:53.185 --> 00:10:55.220 align:start position:0%
- Whether it was really
I did get goose bumps

00:10:55.253 --> 00:10:57.356 align:start position:0%
or I was nervous,
which is why I felt it.

00:10:57.389 --> 00:10:59.324 size:81% position:41%
I know, as a person, like,

00:10:59.357 --> 00:11:00.993 align:start position:0%
if I think there's going
to be pain,

00:11:01.026 --> 00:11:02.127 size:78% position:39%
I'm gonna feel something.

00:11:02.160 --> 00:11:03.929 align:start position:0%
- I do still feel, like,
kind of like

00:11:03.962 --> 00:11:05.330 align:start position:0%
a burning sensation
on my arms.

00:11:05.363 --> 00:11:06.965
- Really?
- Yeah.

00:11:06.998 --> 00:11:09.201
<i> - The power of suggestion
 is so strong</i>

00:11:09.234 --> 00:11:12.805
<i> that this subject continued to
 imagine a physical sensation,</i>

00:11:12.838 --> 00:11:14.940
<i> even after learning
 it wasn't real.</i>

00:11:14.973 --> 00:11:18.243 align:end position:100%
The name for the effect
is the nocebo effect.

00:11:18.276 --> 00:11:21.814 align:end position:100%
It's a negative effect caused
by nothing but the mind.

00:11:21.847 --> 00:11:23.449 align:start position:0%
- It makes perfect sense,
you know,

00:11:23.482 --> 00:11:25.150 size:75% position:38%
the power of suggestion.

00:11:25.183 --> 00:11:27.119 align:start position:0%
I'm shaky just thinking
about it.

00:11:34.226 --> 00:11:37.763
- Pain and touch are weird.

00:11:37.796 --> 00:11:40.299
But what about when touch
straddles the line

00:11:40.332 --> 00:11:42.835
between pleasure and pain?

00:11:42.868 --> 00:11:44.970
When a sensation
makes you laugh

00:11:45.003 --> 00:11:47.005
and drives you crazy.

00:11:47.038 --> 00:11:48.974
I'm talking about tickling.

00:11:49.007 --> 00:11:51.076
<i> Part of what makes you laugh
 when you're tickled</i>

00:11:51.109 --> 00:11:52.811
<i> is the element of surprise.</i>

00:11:52.844 --> 00:11:55.080
<i> Your brain doesn't know
 exactly what to expect</i>

00:11:55.113 --> 00:11:56.448
<i> or when it's going to happen.</i>

00:11:56.481 --> 00:11:59.051
<i> On the other hand,
 it's impossible</i>

00:11:59.084 --> 00:12:00.819
<i> to tickle yourself.</i>

00:12:00.852 --> 00:12:03.789
<i> If the brain knows
 where and when and how</i>

00:12:03.822 --> 00:12:06.859
<i> you are going to be touched,
 you won't laugh.</i>

00:12:06.892 --> 00:12:09.027
But professors of cognitive
neuroscience

00:12:09.060 --> 00:12:10.896
at the University College
London

00:12:10.929 --> 00:12:14.166 line:0%
have invented
the tickle machine.

00:12:14.199 --> 00:12:16.268 line:0%
<i> Subjects sit in
 the tickle machine</i>

00:12:16.301 --> 00:12:17.936 line:0%
<i> with their feet against
 a brush</i>

00:12:17.969 --> 00:12:19.471 line:0%
<i> that is connected
 to a handle.</i>

00:12:19.504 --> 00:12:21.974
<i> At first, when the subjects
 turn the handle,</i>

00:12:22.007 --> 00:12:24.443
<i> the brush rotates
 at the exact same time</i>

00:12:24.476 --> 00:12:26.411
<i> resulting in no tickling.</i>

00:12:26.444 --> 00:12:29.348
<i> Then the machine is switched
 into tickle mode...</i>

00:12:29.381 --> 00:12:31.784
- [laughing] 
<i> -  Which causes a delay</i>

00:12:31.817 --> 00:12:33.452
<i> of less than a second
 between when the subject</i>

00:12:33.485 --> 00:12:35.454
<i> turns the handle
 and when the brush moves</i>

00:12:35.487 --> 00:12:36.922
<i> against their foot.</i>

00:12:36.955 --> 00:12:39.391
- [laughing]
<i> - This slight change</i>

00:12:39.424 --> 00:12:41.059
<i> is enough to prevent
 the brain's cerebellum</i>

00:12:41.092 --> 00:12:42.928
<i> from predicting
 the sensation,</i>

00:12:42.961 --> 00:12:45.931
<i> thus allowing the subject
 to respond to the tickle.</i>

00:12:45.964 --> 00:12:47.933 align:start size:38% position:63%
- [laughing]

00:12:47.966 --> 00:12:49.334
- Tickles can be fun.

00:12:49.367 --> 00:12:52.337
Pain, not so much.

00:12:52.370 --> 00:12:56.441
If you couldn't feel pain,
that would be great, right?

00:12:56.474 --> 00:12:58.143
Or would it?

00:12:58.176 --> 00:13:01.079
Let's meet Steve Pete.

00:13:01.112 --> 00:13:03.448
Steve, I understand
you don't feel pain.

00:13:03.481 --> 00:13:05.450 align:end position:100%
- Yes, I was born
with a rare genetic condition

00:13:05.483 --> 00:13:08.220 align:end position:100% line:0%
called congenital insensitivity
to pain.

00:13:08.253 --> 00:13:10.956
It only affects about 40 to 50
of us around the world with it.

00:13:10.989 --> 00:13:12.424
- Only 40 or 50 people?
- Yeah.

00:13:12.457 --> 00:13:14.226 align:end position:100%
So far that we've been able
to find.

00:13:14.259 --> 00:13:16.995 align:start position:0%
- And tell me what it means when
you say you don't feel pain.

00:13:17.028 --> 00:13:19.464 align:end position:100% line:0%
- Pain is used
to detect injury

00:13:19.497 --> 00:13:21.333 align:end position:100% line:0%
and it kind of sends a signal
to your brain saying,

00:13:21.366 --> 00:13:23.836 align:end position:100% line:0%
"Hey, don't do this anymore."
It's an alarm system.

00:13:23.869 --> 00:13:26.104 align:end position:100%
So what happens
with my condition is

00:13:26.137 --> 00:13:27.539 align:start size:72% position:28%
we feel what's going on

00:13:27.572 --> 00:13:29.408 align:end position:100%
like if I were to touch
your shoulder,

00:13:29.441 --> 00:13:31.009 align:end position:100%
you would feel me
touching your shoulder,

00:13:31.042 --> 00:13:33.011 align:start size:69% position:31%
but if I were to touch
your shoulder in a way

00:13:33.044 --> 00:13:36.014 align:end position:100%
that's painful,
I would feel just a pressure,

00:13:36.047 --> 00:13:39.117 align:end position:100%
and the signal of pain
would not travel to my brain.

00:13:39.150 --> 00:13:41.253
- Okay, so you feel everything--
- Everything else.

00:13:41.286 --> 00:13:44.423 align:start position:0%
that I feel,
but you just don't feel pain.

00:13:44.456 --> 00:13:46.391
- Yeah. Correct.
- But that could be dangerous.

00:13:46.424 --> 00:13:49.361 size:88% position:44%
How did you first find out
that you had this condition?

00:13:49.394 --> 00:13:51.330 align:end position:100%
- Well, what happened was
I was teething

00:13:51.363 --> 00:13:54.032 align:end position:100%
and I chewed
part of my tongue off.

00:13:54.065 --> 00:13:56.368 align:end position:100%
<i> So my parents quickly took me
 to my pediatrician.</i>

00:13:56.401 --> 00:13:58.904
- Wow. Are you ticklish?
- Yes.

00:13:58.937 --> 00:14:00.072
- Do you itch?
- Yes.

00:14:00.105 --> 00:14:01.540
- Do you like massages?
- Yes.

00:14:01.573 --> 00:14:03.508
- Do you take painkillers?
- No.

00:14:03.541 --> 00:14:05.277
- What about a headache?
- No.

00:14:05.310 --> 00:14:08.914
- What about spicy peppers?
- I enjoy them, yeah.

00:14:08.947 --> 00:14:11.950 align:end position:100%
I mean, I do sense
the burning sensation,

00:14:11.983 --> 00:14:13.185 align:start size:63% position:38%
but nothing painful.

00:14:13.218 --> 00:14:17.189 align:start position:0%
- What about intestine pain
like gas pain?

00:14:17.222 --> 00:14:18.624 align:end position:100%
- That's something
I don't feel,

00:14:18.657 --> 00:14:22.327 align:end position:100%
so that kind of ties into
one of my biggest fears,

00:14:22.360 --> 00:14:24.162 align:end position:100%
which is having, like,
appendicitis

00:14:24.195 --> 00:14:26.164 align:end position:100%
or any other type
of internal damage

00:14:26.197 --> 00:14:28.433 align:end position:100%
that I just don't know about
until it's too late.

00:14:28.466 --> 00:14:29.935
- Is there an upside to this?

00:14:29.968 --> 00:14:31.470 align:start position:0%
I'm sure that people,
often naively,

00:14:31.503 --> 00:14:32.938
hear that you don't feel pain...
- Yeah.

00:14:32.971 --> 00:14:34.039 align:start position:0%
- And they think,
"Oh, man.

00:14:34.072 --> 00:14:35.240 align:start position:0%
Well, you should become
a boxer."

00:14:35.273 --> 00:14:37.276 align:end position:100%
- The only upside to it is,
uh,

00:14:37.309 --> 00:14:40.012
<i> being that I have had so many
 injuries during my childhood,</i>

00:14:40.045 --> 00:14:42.514
<i> as I get older, I won't feel
 the pain that comes with it.</i>

00:14:42.547 --> 00:14:44.082
<i> Other than that, really,</i>

00:14:44.115 --> 00:14:45.651
<i> I just try to live
 my life normally</i>

00:14:45.684 --> 00:14:47.152
<i> as everyone else does.</i>

00:14:47.185 --> 00:14:49.421 align:start position:0%
- I cannot describe
pain to you.

00:14:49.454 --> 00:14:52.291
Just like you can't describe
a color to someone who's blind.

00:14:52.324 --> 00:14:54.059 align:end position:100%
- Which is where I run into
my problem

00:14:54.092 --> 00:14:56.662 align:end position:100%
with trying to describe
what not feeling pain is like.

00:14:56.695 --> 00:14:58.563 align:start position:0%
- Wow, I'll bet.

00:14:58.596 --> 00:15:00.032 align:start position:0%
Well, Steve,
thank you very much.

00:15:00.065 --> 00:15:04.303 align:start position:0%
This was really,
really fascinating.

00:15:04.336 --> 00:15:09.574
<i> So not being able to feel pain
 is actually a bad thing.</i>

00:15:09.607 --> 00:15:13.412
But likewise, the anticipation
of pain can be bad too.

00:15:13.445 --> 00:15:17.482
Just making someone think
that they might be tortured soon

00:15:17.515 --> 00:15:19.451
